Parliament has not ratified the amendment for Tymosenko's release
The Ukrainian Parliament refused, as part of an amendment to criminal law, the draft revocation of the paragraph relating to the indictment of Julia Tymosenko, the head of the opposition.
Members refused at second reading the draft amendment aimed at reducing penalties for economic offences, which could have opened the doors of freedom for the former Prime Minister currently imprisoned.
Tymosenko was sentenced to 7 years in prison in October for having concluded a pre-defenced agreement with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is not final and the court must decide on the appeal of the convicted person in December.
Tymosenko described the judgment as political vengeance of the regime and caused a process of suspicion of partiality of the court also in the west.
The draft annulment of paragraph 365 of criminal law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was signed by 147 MEPs.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve it.
