How have travel prices evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered travel, especially in the countries of the socialist bloc, because travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for holidays in East Germany, the Soviet Union (Sotchi, Crimea and Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A great exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when it was authorized to travel to Yugoslavia and the regime began to have an inclination for the West and travel to Yugoslavia was very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not permitted for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovakias) to travel individually even within the socialist countries.
In the event that the Czechoslovakia citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or to the Soviet Union, he needed a letter of invitation otherwise the individual journey was not authorized.
Travel agencies at that time also offered travel to the west, however, you had to make the queue all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that it was not yet won.
The agreement for the currencies that was the condition to travel west was refused to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
However, the Czechoslovakia currency was not exchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial resources without the currency agreement (western currency) to travel west.
Most often the Czechs spent their holidays in the country where there were therefore many country houses and chalets that the Czechs bought and this habit lasts until now.
Since 1989, the Czechs have experienced a great revolution.
Although until 1989 the holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were maximum, the Czechs spent 4 million holidays abroad last year in countries around the world.
The great paradox we do not know today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because of part of Yugoslavia of that time.
The removal of visas in the 1990s in the western neighbouring countries has led to a huge wave of short-term visits, especially in Austria in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovakias could not travel by plane west for a long time that everyone wanted to see for at least a minute.
For example, in Paris travel organisations made the Czechs sleep in tents in the parks because our income did not allow us to pay the hotel or a pension.
The typical feature of a Czech trip was at that time to take his own preserved food, saucish, etc... to save.
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech crown, which finally allowed our tourists to buy freely Western currency after decades.
Our standard of living as well as average wages have increased, which has caused another important moment around 1997.
Thanks to an increasing demand for travel, travel agencies have begun to prepare tours with air charter connections since 1997 which, thanks to contracts, have greatly reduced costs compared to what was before.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs had visa-free connections with virtually most developed countries around the world except the EU that later facilitated our journeys.
Another interesting moment in the post-revolutionary tourism history when the first air charter was prepared for an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic.
Since this year as every year, direct air charters take Czech tourists to the far-reaching hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolution development arrived in 2008.
on 17 November 2008, the EU abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to be fully included in the group of developed countries.
In 2008, the Czechs also spent more than half of their holidays abroad for the first time in history (50.3%) and for the first time again in history spent more than 15,000 kronor per person for holidays abroad including the associated charges.
