In the first year of Mario López Valdez's management, in Sinaloa unemployment and informality increased, foreign investment declined and the economy contracted
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of the Government of Mario López Valdez, self-called change, which has generated great expectations of economic advances, but given the climate adversity of the beginning of the year, the rise is not observed, in exchange for a deterioration of the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures in February, apart from causing billions of losses for the agricultural sector, limited the potential of the state economy for growth, caused a decline in economic activity in general by 3.6% in the first half of the year, mainly justified by the historical decline of 31.16 per cent in agriculture, which affected the dynamics of other economic sectors.
According to the Mexican Council on Sustainable Rural Development, there were damages of 582 million 835 hectares cultivated, one 78.03 per cent of which suffered total damage and the rest of 21.07 per cent suffered partial damage, the main damaged crops were vegetables, corn and chicken peas.
The decline in economic activity generated, up to November, a constant increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the unemployment rate of the State during the first three quarters of the year was accelerated, since while from January to March 55,000, 053,053, were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 per cent of the Active Economic Population, in the second quarter the rate became 5.28 per cent and from July to September the average continued to rise to 6.19 per cent, a rate of over 74,000, an increase compared to the first half of 18,000, 969.
Decreasing liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to economist Gerardo López Cervantes, Director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly according to public policy actions.
"What is observed is an increase in unemployment that is due to various factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to a limitation of resources by the law approved in Congress to combat money laundering, because for people who earn dollars illegally, it is not easy that they work to win them, invest them and use them in something," he said.
Emigrants
López Cervantes reported that the increase in unemployment was also due to a demographic factor.
"The number of people who abandon the state to go to work abroad in the United States has been limited, first because of the entry difficulties and secondly because they already have a lot of difficulty in finding work, these people are staying here and asking for sources of work, which makes unemployment rise," he said.
Deficiency of seriousness
The analysis of the salalon labour market is worsening in view of the high level of seriousness that predominates between the working conditions, according to INEGI, the 60.38 per cent of the population employed in this state is working there without contributing as a worker in any social insurance institution.
Apart from unemployment and the lack of seriousness, another reason for disparity for the state is the low wages, the entity has the lower wages in the country, according to the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Labour Secretariat and Social Forecast.
The average monthly income of the Sinalo workers was, up to September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, much lower than the national average, which is 7 thousand 375 pesos.
IED contraction
In addition to the decline in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, in 2011, the highest reduction in Foreign Direct Investment in the past 10 years was recorded, according to the Economic Secretariat from January to June, the State EDI reached $630,000,697, which represents a decrease of $87.74 per cent compared to $5 million 143,000,312 registered in the same period of the previous year.
In turn, the Economic Development Secretariat of the Government of the State accounts for a total of 17,280 billion pesos per year, registered mainly by tertiary companies.
Debt
In view of the economic downturn scenario, the Government of the State requested the public Congress in July to approve a 3 billion pesos credit for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the aim of reactivating the economy, the approval of the State Congress was 2,600 billion pesos, and until November there was no benefit from debt in any sector of the state economy.
Responses
For the representatives of the employer sector, the first year of the Government of Mario López Valdés demonstrates a lack of management capacity of the Government.
Miguel Loredo López, President of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 there was no harmonisation of the wishes of the various sectors, including the Government of the State.
"The performance of the Sinaloa economy during this year has been really very poor, we have to work intensively to recover the land we lost this year, in 2012 we have to double our efforts, we have had to align the effort of all, and above all the already synchronized progress of this new government team, hoping that next year will be much better," he said.
Economic slowdown
Loredo López stated that events such as the frosts of the beginning of the year have retained the state economy and have reduced its yield and growth.
"The low economic flow is produced from several events, including freezing, one of the main effects was a slow economy that does not turn quickly enough to generate economic dynamics that allows for an acceptable level of flow in trials, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year, we close much below the expectations we had," he said.
Redefined vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, the president of the Patronal Confederation of the Mexican Republic of Sinaloa said that we want to channel the state to productive activities of greater dynamism.
"In general terms, we have observed that work has been done, we think it is necessary to develop a long-term programme that redefined the vocation and economic direction of the State, because it is important that all the potential of Sinaloa's material and human resources be explored," he said.
Much to do
