The Court validates "analog cut" in Mexico in 2015
Replacement of analog signals with digitals is one of the most important changes the world has suffered in recent years
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) has debushed the constitutional controversies that the Senate and the House of Deputies have expressed against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analytical cut" from 2021 to 2015, because the eight votes necessary to invalidate it have not been gathered.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his responsibilities when he issued the decree detailing the actions to be taken to achieve the transition to terrestrial digital television.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic was debushed for not reaching the qualified majority of eight votes in order for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality of the decree, and this continues to be in force.
The draft sentence, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed the statement of the decree as non-constitutional because the regulation on radio and television is a statutory assignment to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and of the reserve of law.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree and by admitting the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero has suspended the application of the decree and of all its actions for the digital transition.
The plenary meeting of ministers also decided to support the complaint made by the Chamber of Deputies, without discussing the draft of which Minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible.
In his speech, the Minister President said that he disagreed with the project's arguments, in the sense that the Federal Executive cannot structure measures through general standards for public administration to prepare for them.
"I also consider it only if it was done to affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," and he recalled that public policy planning in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, which has the constitutional mandate of the State's leadership.
Replacement of analogue signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes that the world has suffered in recent years, and this results in better radio spectrum use, better signal quality and more channels.
Sustaining change, he supported, would delay the benefits of digitalisation, which involves a decision of public interest which has not only a technical dimension, "for it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues".
These questions, he stressed, "requires the operation of a whole system established, in accordance with the principle of economic leadership of the State, comprises a group of powers which the Constitution grants the authority of the State's Executive".
He recalled that a large number of countries from all have already completed the digital transition and have done so through the Executive, despite the fact that they have highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the contested decree, has invaded in a form the sphere of competence of the Congress, as it ensures in the administrative sphere that the laws issued by the Legislative Act are respected.
