UNAM asphalt would avoid cassis
Rafael Herrera, researcher of the UNAM Department of Chemistry, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions.
If the signals that the pavement were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200 thousand cassis each rain season in the Mexico Metropolitan Area, warns Rafael Herrera Nájera, UNAM's Researcher at the Department of Chemistry (FQ), who has assured that if the construction and maintenance process of the pallet pavement is adequate, the cassis could be reduced or even completely eliminated.
During his conference A technical opinion on cassis, organized in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory responsible for it develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with similar characteristics to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Mrera Nájera considered that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve efficiency, and consequently, the formation of cassis.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier share of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphalts, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called malthenes, which together give the pavee its viscoelastic behaviour characteristic.
The viscoelastic behaviour of the asphalt consists of the fact that at high temperatures, almost 180 degrees, is acting as a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees C it has a almost solid state, while at very low temperatures the asphalt becomes broken, added it.
This means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, advises the chemical engineering specialist.
The researcher of the QF observed that the streets of Ciudad de Mexico, in their majority, were covered by a flexible pavement, consisting of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Between the more surface layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and compressed later.
Each of the small stones that form the layer, signaled it, is bathed year asphalt.
When vehicles pass there by generating efforts, this allows the forces to spread very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, they would spread better, only the chemical ingredient.
On the asphalt layer, he said, a last layer called the rolling layer, made of fine stone, i.e. sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt layer and provide adhesion in the street.
As the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the effort, the rolling layer also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material it is made must be treated.
The climate, especially the humidity and temperature variations, is also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, as these significantly affect the efficiency of the asphalt layer.
When the floor wets, the water spreads inside the layer, it is difficult for it to come out, which ramolates all the layers of the paved and therefore causes cassis.
In the process of formation of a cassis, he said, the first thing that blew is the rolling film and only later is affected the asphalt layer, but the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that must be treated to the first signals with appropriate maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor for cassis formation and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pad must always be linked to the load of vehicles and ensure its satisfaction, in order to avoid frequent cassis formation.
Rafael Herrera has warned that there is still a lot to invest and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow to repair cassis easily and without having to use high temperatures.
