As a result, experts quote a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries of the world.
While Canada ranked 10th, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has created a culture in which people are afraid to address the subject of death."
Medicinalization or not, 77% of Canadians have no access to palliative care, reports experts mandated by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the desire that most Canadians have to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying in the hospital.
Overall, this is the highest rate in Quebec, with 86% of the deaths in the hospital.
On the delicate issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that are contrary to the position of the federal government, which has already said that there is no wish to change the Criminal Code on euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also reviewed all countries where these approaches are legalized or descriptive, there is no evidence that such descriptiveization leads to abuse in the application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or suicide assisted in non-competent or non-consent persons.
On the contrary, yesterday, at a teleconference Jocelyn Downie, a co-signatorie of the report, there would be more cases of these excesses in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
"Uthanasia is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal."
"Assisted suicide is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal," Jocelyn Downie explains.
Canadians in favour of euthanasia
