Nord Stream, a new Russian gas gate in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, connecting West Europe directly to Russia through the bottom of the Baltic Sea, entered service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with joy.
More than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated, last Tuesday, on the edges of the Baltic, between orchestra and end buffet, in the inauguration of Nord Stream, this new gas pipeline that directly connects Russia, under the sea, to Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart from the Netherlands Mark Rutte turned together the pilot of the valve commanding the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new gas pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic metres of Russian gas will arrive every year in Western Europe through a first 1,224 km tube connecting the region of Saint Petersburg to the Land of Mecklembourg-Pomerania.
A second tube should be completed at the end of 2012, allowing a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, equivalent to all French consumption.
And we are already referring to the possibility of building a third on the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion in time and hour of this huge yard has a winning look.
The project had been strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic countries.
Nord Stream will be able to deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding land crossings through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries lose a little of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close its access to the Western European markets.
In the strongest of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare Nord Stream with a "new German-Soviet Pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Staline to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the subject is politically sensitive.
West Europe, with its support for this Russian project, has gained greater security in its supplies.
But this is at the cost of weakening Europe of energy, as the project has created a break between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has been able to triumph with its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, with strong gas consumption, and its deposits are declining.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us organically," confirmed François Fillon by inaugurating this gas pipeline, showing how the major gas contracts are as political as well as economic.
All this explains the wide smiles shown by the leaders of Gazprom, present in number in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical exploitation.
The underwater tube is made of concrete steel in order to protect it from the anchors of the ships.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 m.
To build it, mine fields from World War II had to be avoided.
"A hundred had to be removed or destroyed by caution," says Jens Müller, spokesperson of Nord Stream.
There was also a need to increase measures to protect wildlife and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy like 242 Eiffel towers, which nothing interrupts throughout its length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned outside Sweden, but the project leaders abandoned it, while the Swedish were unwilling to see a Russian state company permanently established outside their coasts.
"In case of injury, we stop the gas passage in less than one minute," says Jens Müller.
In the event of leakage, the gas contained in the gas pipeline escapes from the air.
However, this is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who have planned the welding to experience a leak every 100,000 years.
The state of the gas pipeline is monitored by a submarine robot, dragged by a ship, for external observation, as well as by a device operating inside the gas pipeline.
From the form of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, wide of a metre of diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
On arrival, after three full days of trip at a speed of 3 seconds, he provides precise information on possible metal deformations.
The gas pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without having to undergo any repair.
The flow of gas is simply ensured by pressure.
It is 200 bars on departure, and 100 on arrival.
Five companies have united their forces to implement this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, who holds 51% of the shares.
The Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each) as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have established a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It has its seat in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented to this company for 20 years of renewable gas transport capacity.
"Gazprom will pay for total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the gas pipeline was provided by the shareholders at 30% and by banks at 70%.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach €7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment rose to 240 million.
However, minority shareholders are sure to return to their costs, since Gazprom alone assumes the risk.
The Baltic gas pipeline emerges in Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine.
Ventiles with a height of 4.5 metres form the gas exit door.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that arrives before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has received one million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour.
With full capacity, this will be 3 million per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine, a brand book.
Created 15 years ago by an Italian company, the Moleskin wants to restore the taste of writing.
It has a scent of adventures, hours past to write in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine book is easily recognisable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its broken white leaves, as old-fashioned by time.
However, the Moleskin book as we know today was born in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, at the time decided to launch a design but distinguished notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant for the company, is responsible for launching the new product.
The booklet is based on an old production technique, the mole of skin (muffle skin), which refers to a laminated cotton used to cover benches, for example.
This type of book was very pleased with writers and travellers.
"Moleskine gave to the taste of the day an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of avant-garde artists, up to the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who became responsible for the brand at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12,7 million out of stock.
We are far from the confidential production of the first years, where only 3,000 carnets were designed.
Moleskin crosses Italian borders and exports to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
Difficult to establish a buyer's robot portrait, because the notebook attracts businessman as well as students and professionals.
Like Moleskin, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open and cultivated.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees at its beginnings, now accounts almost 100 and has two offices since 2008, one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her books in the libraries, from Fnac to small town shops and has been able to impose her identity.
"We followed the air of time and this new need for writing, despite the growing emails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskin: recently, the brand launched an exhibition " Detour " where architects or artists exhibit their own book.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover at the Locarno Film Festival.
Enjoying its success and its cultural will, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, calendars, pens, computer boxes... The brand falls on a wide range of mediums.
A success that made envy: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was purchased by the SG Capital Europe Investment Fund, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskin's history.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week for the employment of disabled people is open today.
Despite a voluntary public policy in 2005, the unemployment rate of disabled persons is still twice as high as the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the total population.
Discouraging?
"No," stresses Eric Blanchet, Director General of the Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of disabled people. "
"The progress made over the past 15 years is considerable. "
At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice as high as three.
"However, there is still a lot to do."
It must be said that for disabled unemployed, many obstacles remain before access to employment.
They are rather older: 37% are over 50 years of age (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% of the 2.3 million students in higher education are disabled only 10,000.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for disabled persons, compared with an average of 38%.
In short, so many criteria that make it particularly difficult to return to employment, and which are "the key to the problem", according to Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, an association established in 1992 to help firms recruit disabled workers.
This is for objective brakes.
Rest the unnoticed, the mentalities that evolve, though, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Enterprise Association for the City indicated that the respondent managers have "a low level of knowledge of disability", with "overrepresentation of wheelchairs, mental or intellectual deficiencies".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, as set out in a 1987 Act.
The latest known figures, dating from 2008, reported a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, Director General of the Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The evidence: the number of "taxed" establishments, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Act, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on businesses," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects real awareness, especially in large groups."
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments of 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of enterprises of 100 to 199 employees.
